e critical for managing claim expectations and insurer liability [Data: Entities (57), Relationships (86, 101, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Prohibition on combining coverage limits across vehicles\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The rule 'Combining Limits Prohibited' explicitly states that coverage limits from multiple vehicles cannot be aggregated during a single accident. If an accident involves one vehicle, only the coverage limits for that specific vehicle apply. This rule prevents policyholders from increasing their total liability protection by combining multiple vehicles’ limits. However, if no vehicle is involved—such as in a third-party injury claim—the policy allows selecting the limits of a single vehicle to apply. This rule ensures fairness and prevents abuse of the policy structure, maintaining the integrity of the vehicle-specific coverage model. It also simplifies claims processing by eliminating the need to calculate combined limits, reducing administrative complexity. The rule is directly tied to how coverage limits are applied per auto, as confirmed in the relationship between Combining Limits Prohibited and Coverage Limits [Data: Entities (49), Relationships (101, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Coverage changes are formally documented and impact limits\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The Policy Declarations allow for updates to coverage terms and limits during the policy period through formal changes, such as increasing liability limits or adding new vehicles. These changes are documented in the Coverage Change entity and are reflected in the Policy Declarations, ensuring that the updated terms remain legally binding. A coverage change may include an increase or modification of coverage limits, which are then formally recorded and applied to the relevant vehicle(s). This dynamic feature allows policyholders to adapt their coverage to changing needs, such as purchasing a new vehi